the various successor powers fighting against each other kind of seem to be at a, well, impasse, though the advantage tends towards our protagonist powers; the western powers seem rather aligned with each other and with an overseas communist power bloc, whereas the southerners are apparently living in a complete nuclear hellhole (though florida is still gone :crab:), mexico appears to be opposed to this power bloc, and just no one likes the remnants of the us (except for the mexicans). this decisively puts the advantage in the hands of the two socialist powers, thanks to their large population base in california and potential overseas industrial base.

i'm fairly certain if it weren't for the fact that the great plains fell to warlordism and that most big powers in america seem to have nuclear deterrents then the west would absolutely steamroll the east- as it is, though, they seem to be content to keep out of the mudpit in the center of the continent and build up for a future unification campaign.

an:

pas' armed forces make experimental use of mechs in an anti-tank role; the primary purpose of these mechs seems to be, based on the capabilities they have, to equip forces with the flexibility of infantry formations and the speed of armored forces to- in a nutshell- out-traverse tanks in urban combat and then just rip into tanks that lack the offensive capabilities needed to engage with said mechs. i can imagine that this would push for the development of strong over-the-horizon engagement capabilities among their enemies, but then again, such capabilities aren't as effective in urban environments and i can also imagine the absolute hell they would wreak in the sort of hyper-urban environments pas' cities are made to be.

by CBG-Palisade » Sun Feb 21, 2021 7:39 pm

more of an ooc thing but i've learned that diarcesia's primary worldbuilding formula is through collections of notes or bullet-points. this lends itself towards making things convenient to digest, but complicates things somewhat when people look for something to dig into; the content isn't such that there's paragraphs to immerse oneself in, but rather interesting if somewhat disjointed bullet points. diarcesia goes at things from the bottom up rather than the top down- worlds are constructed through individual notes and snippets rather than built out from overarching views of a broad picture, which i find absolutely fascinating to try and go through, tbh. quite interesting.
